00:14:52,110 --> 00:14:54,635
That's all I've ever wanted to be.

239
00:14:58,750 --> 00:15:01,514
The ring your father
gave your mother, I believe.

240
00:15:01,920 --> 00:15:03,683
[ARTHUR SIGHS]

241
00:15:05,423 --> 00:15:07,186
It's like an ice rink for a mouse.

242
00:15:08,627 --> 00:15:09,753
I don't like Susan.

243
00:15:09,928 --> 00:15:13,887
Well, I don't like you very much and we've
been happily stuck together for 30 years.

244
00:15:14,065 --> 00:15:17,432
I know it's not perfect,
but Susan is smart and capable...

245
00:15:17,602 --> 00:15:20,002
...and you need a woman like that
to look after you.

246
00:15:20,171 --> 00:15:25,074
I think I already have one of those.
In fact, do you want it?

247
00:15:26,277 --> 00:15:31,613
Hobson, will you carry on
being my nanny?

248
00:15:32,150 --> 00:15:34,550
This is just my mother
trying to control me.

249
00:15:35,153 --> 00:15:37,178
Hey, Hobson, do you have the checkbook?

250
00:15:37,355 --> 00:15:39,220
I wanna squander some wealth.

251
00:15:39,391 --> 00:15:42,292
AUCTIONEER: Ten thousand dollars
for this item from the czar's collection.

252
00:15:42,460 --> 00:15:46,760
Are we all done at 10,000? Ten thousand
dollars going once, going twice.

253
00:15:48,166 --> 00:15:50,532
Twenty thousand dollars of money!

254
00:15:50,702 --> 00:15:52,567
Twenty thousand dollars is the bid.

255
00:15:52,737 --> 00:15:54,602
Thank you, sir. Do I hear 30?
Do I hear 30,000?

256
00:15:54,773 --> 00:15:56,638
[IN DEEP VOICE]
Thirty thousand dollars, please.

257
00:15:56,808 --> 00:15:57,866
AUCTIONEER:
Thirty thousand.

258
00:15:58,043 --> 00:15:59,533
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Thirty-five thousand.

259
00:15:59,711 --> 00:16:02,373
[ALTERNATING VOICES] How dare you.
It's a challenge you want, is it?

260
00:16:02,547 --> 00:16:04,708
Yeah, I want a challenge, plus I bid first.

261
00:16:04,883 --> 00:16:08,114
That is irrelevant.
The highest number has supremacy.

262
00:16:08,286 --> 00:16:09,878
You've clearly never been to an auction.

263
00:16:10,055 --> 00:16:11,249
That's tit for tat.

264
00:16:11,423 --> 00:16:13,687
That's exactly how the situation
in the Middle East began.

265
00:16:13,858 --> 00:16:15,917
You leave me no choice.

266
00:16:16,094 --> 00:16:18,961
One hundred thousand dollars
and one penny...

267
00:16:19,130 --> 00:16:22,964
...because you, sir, are a vile spendthrift.

268
00:16:23,134 --> 00:16:26,069
Well, that's the first sensible thing
you've said all day.

269
00:16:27,205 --> 00:16:31,699
Sold to one of the Mr. Bachs
for $100,000 and one penny.

270
00:16:31,876 --> 00:16:33,935
- Thank you, sirs.
HOBSON: Congratulations.

271
00:16:34,379 --> 00:16:35,676
Hey, come on, Hobson.

272
00:16:35,847 --> 00:16:38,611
You know I've always coveted
the cutlery of Czar Nicholas II.

273
00:16:38,783 --> 00:16:40,478
- Me too.
ARTHUR: Oh.

274
00:16:41,052 --> 00:16:43,111
Our last item up for bid today:

275
00:16:43,288 --> 00:16:46,746
The suit in which Abraham Lincoln
delivered his second inaugural address.

276
00:16:47,759 --> 00:16:50,421
Let's start the bidding at 50,000.
Do I hear 50,000?

277
00:16:50,795 --> 00:16:52,592
[IN DEEP VOICE] I'll take it.

278
00:16:52,764 --> 00:16:55,426
[IN NORMAL VOICE] And the teleportation
device in which it stands.

279
00:16:56,768 --> 00:17:00,363
If you think this represents a victory
over your mother's financial tyranny...

280
00:17:00,538 --> 00:17:02,972
...you're deluded.
- Thanks for the spoon, Arthur.

281
00:17:03,141 --> 00:17:06,577
- Anytime. Buy me a fork one day.
- Where's Bitterman with the car?

282
00:17:06,778 --> 00:17:09,042
He said he was gonna be
by the big gray thing.

283
00:17:09,214 --> 00:17:10,476
- Where?
- He said...

284
00:17:10,648 --> 00:17:13,481
...the big gray sculpture thing
with things on it.

285
00:17:13,651 --> 00:17:16,142
It was like a riddle.
He can be very vague.

286
00:17:16,321 --> 00:17:18,516
It's the blind leading the drunk.

287
00:17:18,690 --> 00:17:21,284
ARTHUR: Hobson, you find Bitterman
while I wander off.

288
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:30,160
Wow.

289
00:17:30,335 --> 00:17:31,359
What is this for?

290
00:17:31,936 --> 00:17:33,927
Where's everyone going?

291
00:17:34,105 --> 00:17:37,836
NAOMI: This is actually not Grand Central
Station, it's Grand Central Terminal.

292
00:17:38,009 --> 00:17:39,135
- Oh.
- Oh!

293
00:17:39,310 --> 00:17:42,711
- Sorry.
- No, no, I was static in a thoroughfare.

294
00:17:43,581 --> 00:17:46,982
Uh, I'm lost. Do you know where I can get
a drink, please?

295
00:17:47,152 --> 00:17:48,312
Um...

296
00:17:50,522 --> 00:17:51,955
This is really all I have.

297
00:17:52,557 --> 00:17:53,854
Good luck.

298
00:17:54,025 --> 00:17:55,117
- Come on.
- Coins.

299
00:17:55,293 --> 00:17:59,195
- I played with these when I was a boy.
NAOMI: Let's keep going. Time's a wasting.

300
00:17:59,364 --> 00:18:00,695
Speaking of time...

301
00:18:00,865 --> 00:18:04,824
...the clock behind me is one of the
most expensive clocks in the world.

302
00:18:05,003 --> 00:18:06,698
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

303
00:18:12,043 --> 00:18:14,409
NAOMI: Thousands of people
pass through here every day...

304
00:18:14,579 --> 00:18:16,945
...and no one ever bothers to look up.

305
00:18:17,115 --> 00:18:20,812
It's magical. It's the only place
in Manhattan where you can see the stars.

306
00:18:20,985 --> 00:18:24,079
But it wasn't always that way...
Oh, you again.

307
00:18:25,690 --> 00:18:29,649
If you look in the corner you can see
one dirty brick...

308
00:18:29,828 --> 00:18:34,527
...and the whole ceiling used to be
like that until it was renovated in 1998.

309
00:18:34,699 --> 00:18:39,033
Wow, this is brilliant. If you like ceilings,
I've got a beautiful one above my bed.

310
00:18:39,204 --> 00:18:40,228
[NAOMI SCOFFS]

311
00:18:40,405 --> 00:18:42,669
That sounded cheeky.
I didn't mean that. It lights up.

312
00:18:42,841 --> 00:18:44,103
Thanks for that.

313
00:18:44,275 --> 00:18:47,676
If you direct your attention to the
opposite corner, you'll see a...

314
00:18:48,179 --> 00:18:51,012
...police officer.
- Miss, I warned you about this.

315
00:18:51,182 --> 00:18:53,912
You don't have a tour license
and now you're impeding foot traffic.

316
00:18:54,085 --> 00:18:55,484
Come on, up, up, everybody up.

317
00:18:55,653 --> 00:18:59,555
Officer, which law prevents
this radiant stranger...

318
00:18:59,724 --> 00:19:02,249
...from finding the magical
in the mundane?

319
00:19:02,427 --> 00:19:06,523
- MTA Code 1085.1, Section 5.
- Could you be more specific?

320
00:19:08,766 --> 00:19:11,633
OFFICER: Hey. Hey!
- Oh, there's a chase. We're in a chase.

321
00:19:11,803 --> 00:19:13,361
Sir, grab my Lincoln stick.

322
00:19:13,538 --> 00:19:14,562
Chase!

323
00:19:15,540 --> 00:19:18,065
My mind is racing. My heart is pounding.

324
00:19:18,243 --> 00:19:20,234
This is my first chase, and I love it.

325
00:19:21,312 --> 00:19:24,611
- Let me through, I'm a free spirit!
OFFICER: West on 42nd.

326
00:19:25,216 --> 00:19:26,979
This is what I live for!

327
00:19:27,151 --> 00:19:28,277
OFFICER:
We've got a runner.

328
00:19:28,453 --> 00:19:30,853
ARTHUR: A chase is happening!
This is a genuine chase!

329
00:19:31,022 --> 00:19:32,717
Oh! I'm... I...

330
00:19:32,891 --> 00:19:37,385
- No, no, no.
- I was gonna go get my license.

331
00:19:37,562 --> 00:19:40,258
You ran from me, Naomi.
Now I gotta take you in.

332
00:19:40,431 --> 00:19:43,423
Besides, you've had three warnings
for operating an illegal tour.

333
00:19:43,601 --> 00:19:46,069
Except this isn't an illegal tour...

334
00:19:46,237 --> 00:19:49,604
...because these people aren't tourists,
they're our family.

335
00:19:50,475 --> 00:19:52,841
Yes. They are, they're my family.

336
00:19:53,011 --> 00:19:55,070
That's my family.
We're having a family reunion.

337
00:19:55,246 --> 00:19:58,579
Reunion. Uh, that, for example,
is Uncle Stuart waving there.

338
00:19:58,750 --> 00:20:00,945
NAOMI:
Yes. Oh, hey, Uncle Stuart.

339
00:20:01,119 --> 00:20:04,145
Under that sun hat,
that's Caribbean Diane Keaton.

340
00:20:04,322 --> 00:20:06,790
- Yes, exactly.
- And also we have...

341
00:20:06,958 --> 00:20:09,188
NAOMI:
Uncle Korean John Lennon.

342
00:20:09,661 --> 00:20:12,027
And this is, uh, Abe Lincoln, I presume.

343
00:20:12,196 --> 00:20:13,663
- Oh, no.
ARTHUR: No.

344
00:20:13,831 --> 00:20:18,768
- He is my admittedly eccentric...
- Fiancé. I'm her fiancé.

345
00:20:18,937 --> 00:20:21,269
He is my fiancé.

346
00:20:23,408 --> 00:20:24,875
NAOMI:
Oh. Mm-hm.

347
00:20:27,779 --> 00:20:30,043
Darling, you don't want
these people to think...

348
00:20:30,214 --> 00:20:32,944
...that you're some kind of
random British pervert.

349
00:20:33,117 --> 00:20:37,281
No, I'm a very specific British pervert,
which is why you fell in love with me...

350
00:20:37,455 --> 00:20:40,390
...from our first date.
- Which was where, exactly?

351
00:20:41,793 --> 00:20:42,817
Grand Central.

352
00:20:42,994 --> 00:20:45,724
You had your first date
at Grand Central Station.

353
00:20:45,897 --> 00:20:50,459
It wasn't a shabby affair. I'd hired
out the entire place. It was deserted.

354
00:20:50,635 --> 00:20:53,399
Acrobats were in the place,
put on quite a show for us.

355
00:20:53,604 --> 00:20:55,037
- Didn't they, Naomi?
- No, no.

356
00:20:55,206 --> 00:20:57,401
The floor was strewn
with a million petals.

357
00:20:57,608 --> 00:21:00,168
Their scent hung in the air
like the sweet breath of angels.

358
00:21:00,345 --> 00:21:02,813
And we forgot ourselves entirely.
Didn't we?

359
00:21:02,981 --> 00:21:04,881
And ran nude through that concourse.

360
00:21:05,049 --> 00:21:07,574
No, no, we just...
We had clothes on and we ate.

361
00:21:07,752 --> 00:21:09,481
- What'd you eat?
NAOMI: Oh.

362
00:21:09,654 --> 00:21:11,053
Oh, what was that?

363
00:21:11,222 --> 00:21:12,689
NAOMI: Pe...
ARTHUR: Pe... Pe... Pe...

364
00:21:12,857 --> 00:21:13,881
[BOTH]
PEZ.

365
00:21:14,058 --> 00:21:16,151
Have any identification, Mr. Lincoln?

366
00:21:16,327 --> 00:21:17,658
ARTHUR:
Actually, I do.

367
00:21:17,829 --> 00:21:21,196
Um, here you go. I think you'll find that
should do the trick.

368
00:21:21,366 --> 00:21:24,062
There's plenty more where that
came from, if you catch my drift, hmm?

369
00:21:24,235 --> 00:21:26,760
Ah. You keep it, Arthur,
and thank you for the show.

370
00:21:26,938 --> 00:21:28,269
[ARTHUR CHUCKLES]

371
00:21:28,439 --> 00:21:31,169
- Naomi, get a license. Good luck.
NAOMI: Okay.

372
00:21:32,343 --> 00:21:34,675
What was that? Who are you?

373
00:21:34,846 --> 00:21:38,782
I'm just a ragged-trousered stranger
with a crazy hat.

374
00:21:38,950 --> 00:21:40,884
Oh, my God.

375
00:21:42,186 --> 00:21:46,316
Arthur, your safari into the pointless
ends now. Get in the car.

376
00:21:46,491 --> 00:21:49,756
No. It's okay.
Uh, Hobson can't tell me what to do.

377
00:21:49,927 --> 00:21:53,419
Yes, I can. I work for his mother.
Get in the car. Bitterman, open the door.

378
00:21:54,732 --> 00:21:57,667
ARTHUR: Bitterman, close that door.
- Get in the car.

379
00:21:57,835 --> 00:21:59,735
- Not you, Bitterman.
ARTHUR: Yes, you, Bitterman.

380
00:21:59,904 --> 00:22:02,930
I'm sorry. Who are you people?

381
00:22:03,107 --> 00:22:04,438
I'm his nanny.

382
00:22:05,643 --> 00:22:06,940
I'm not, I'm Bitterman.

383
00:22:07,111 --> 00:22:11,445
Well, I have to get back to our confused
family over there, so have a nice day.

384
00:22:11,616 --> 00:22:12,947
ARTHUR:
Oh, hang... Uh, excuse me.

385
00:22:13,751 --> 00:22:16,948
Naomi Quinn,
I'd like to see you again.

386
00:22:17,121 --> 00:22:20,557
- I don't date boys who have nannies.
HOBSON: Very wise choice.

387
00:22:20,725 --> 00:22:23,660
You're not the first woman
who walks the streets for a living...

388
00:22:23,828 --> 00:22:25,295
...that he's taken a liking to.

389
00:22:26,931 --> 00:22:28,296
Is she always with you?

390
00:22:30,768 --> 00:22:35,102
Okay. 917-176-2030.

391
00:22:35,273 --> 00:22:37,935
- Uh... Did you remember that?
- No.

392
00:22:41,979 --> 00:22:43,708
[CHEERING AND APPLAUDING]

393
00:22:44,482 --> 00:22:45,813
Arthur, get in the car.

394
00:22:47,118 --> 00:22:51,987
I'm gonna get in the car now, but because
I want to, not because you have told me to.

395
00:22:52,323 --> 00:22:53,756
Distinction.

396
00:22:53,925 --> 00:22:55,187
Bitterman.

397
00:22:55,793 --> 00:22:59,820
ARTHUR: It was magical. We ran
from the police, then we lied to them.

398
00:22:59,997 --> 00:23:02,989
- Have you ever had days like that, Evander?
EVANDER: I believe I have.

399
00:23:04,368 --> 00:23:08,600
Me and this girl are two perfectly matched
opponents, like you and Mike Tyson.

400
00:23:08,773 --> 00:23:10,434
- She could be the one.
ARTHUR: Yes.

401
00:23:10,608 --> 00:23:13,338
Oh. I'm so sorry. That went
right through your guard.

402
00:23:13,511 --> 00:23:15,672
- Are you okay?
- I'll make it.

403
00:23:15,847 --> 00:23:17,371
What I like about her, Naomi...

404
00:23:17,548 --> 00:23:20,108
...is she's got a very unique way
of seeing the world.

405
00:23:20,284 --> 00:23:21,546
So do flies.

406
00:23:21,719 --> 00:23:25,519
This is a repeat of when you were certain
you needed a pet giraffe to be happy.

407
00:23:25,690 --> 00:23:29,182
- Well, you were bored after a week.
- Because he ate his monocle.

408
00:23:29,360 --> 00:23:31,658
The brute had no regard
for fashion, Evander.

409
00:23:31,829 --> 00:23:34,889
No, because you were from two
different worlds, the same as this girl.

410
00:23:35,066 --> 00:23:38,263
Listen, could you just let me focus
on my jab and refresh me, please?

411
00:23:40,004 --> 00:23:43,064
- Aah! That's vodka in there.
- Refreshed?

412
00:23:43,641 --> 00:23:47,668
No, but I think some of it probably went
in my bloodstream so it's not all bad news.

413
00:23:48,079 --> 00:23:50,138
- Get dressed.
- Why?

414
00:23:50,314 --> 00:23:52,646
Because at 3:00
you're going to ask Burt Johnson...

415
00:23:52,817 --> 00:23:54,751
...for his daughter's hand in marriage.

416
00:23:54,919 --> 00:23:58,252
I will do no such thing. I'm going to
remain here and box with Evander.

417
00:23:58,422 --> 00:24:01,550
And then I shall have my music lesson
with Kanye West as planned.

418
00:24:01,926 --> 00:24:03,484
Out, now.

419
00:24:05,997 --> 00:24:07,726
Make me.

420
00:24:11,035 --> 00:24:12,764
I'll just have a bit of fun with her.

421
00:24:12,937 --> 00:24:14,905
Use the old rope-a-dope,
I should think.

422
00:24:15,072 --> 00:24:18,269
- Stick and move, like you taught me.
- Arthur, after you're married...

423
00:24:18,442 --> 00:24:21,434
...you're going to have to stop this
obsession with random women.

424
00:24:21,612 --> 00:24:24,103
She is not a random woman,
she understands me.

425
00:24:24,282 --> 00:24:28,548
She laughs at my jokes. She's like you, but
with a more appropriate potential for sex.

426
00:24:28,986 --> 00:24:30,283
[ARTHUR YELLS]

427
00:24:31,122 --> 00:24:35,616
Ow! That really hurt. Evander,
you assured me I was indestructible.

428
00:24:35,793 --> 00:24:37,886
Burt Johnson, 3:00.

429
00:24:38,496 --> 00:24:43,661
Evander, if he's not out of this ring
in one minute, I'll bite your other ear off.

430
00:25:01,919 --> 00:25:04,149
What am I doing here, Bitterman?

431
00:25:04,589 --> 00:25:07,717
Uh, you asked me to drive you
to the Burt Johnson Tower.

432
00:25:09,961 --> 00:25:12,828
- But if you were me...
- I would like that very much.

433
00:25:13,097 --> 00:25:14,928
That's very flattering.

434
00:25:15,099 --> 00:25:18,899
But if you were me
and you were in this situation...

435
00:25:19,070 --> 00:25:21,265
...what would you do? What should I say?

436
00:25:21,439 --> 00:25:27,002
Uh, I'd go in there and say, um,
"Mr. Johnson, I like your tower.

437
00:25:28,312 --> 00:25:29,973
But I love your daughter."

438
00:25:30,147 --> 00:25:33,412
- But I don't love his daughter.
- Don't say that, because then he'll say no.

439
00:25:34,619 --> 00:25:36,018
You've been very helpful.

440
00:25:37,888 --> 00:25:40,152
Put this on. Wait here.

441
00:25:40,324 --> 00:25:42,417
It's the same as your one.

442
00:25:42,593 --> 00:25:44,959
"BJ," I'll never get tired of that.

443
00:25:47,765 --> 00:25:48,789
[DOOR CLOSES]

444
00:25:48,966 --> 00:25:49,990
[LOCK CLICKS]

445
00:25:53,371 --> 00:25:55,430
Woo-hoo, Bitterman!

446
00:26:02,380 --> 00:26:03,847
[AIR HISSES]

447
00:26:06,417 --> 00:26:08,715
Bloody hell.

448
00:26:08,986 --> 00:26:10,817
It's an apocalyptic future.

449
00:26:10,988 --> 00:26:14,355
The Upper East Side lay
in absolute ruin.

450
00:26:14,525 --> 00:26:16,686
The machines have taken over, as usual.

451
00:26:16,861 --> 00:26:18,726
Ah, malevolent toaster.

452
00:26:18,929 --> 00:26:21,830
Only one man can save civilization.

453
00:26:21,999 --> 00:26:24,832
And that man is Arthur Bach.

454
00:26:25,002 --> 00:26:26,970
Justice!

455
00:26:40,184 --> 00:26:41,208
Hello, Arthur.

456
00:26:41,385 --> 00:26:45,719
- Uh, sorry, I've never used...
- Never used what, Arthur?

457
00:26:45,890 --> 00:26:48,825
One of these guns what makes nails
come out of it.

458
00:26:48,993 --> 00:26:53,327
Oh, the Grip-Rite GR 350.

459
00:26:53,764 --> 00:26:55,356
It's a good gun.

460
00:26:55,533 --> 00:26:59,128
It's lovely, isn't it?
It's also one of my favorites.

461
00:27:00,171 --> 00:27:02,435
Do you know you've got nails sticking
in you?

462
00:27:02,606 --> 00:27:05,040
Framing nails.

463
00:27:05,409 --> 00:27:07,434
Standard.

464
00:27:08,779 --> 00:27:11,509
Well, I love what
you've done with the place, Burt.

465
00:27:11,682 --> 00:27:14,708
It reminds me of a gay club
I went to once in Copenhagen.

466
00:27:14,885 --> 00:27:17,183
This is gonna be my new office.

467
00:27:17,621 --> 00:27:19,646
Oh, my God. I live right over there.

